	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES/Famicom board - just an idea</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I got a similar idea a couple of months ago, mine was having a hybrid cart that could be plugged in either system. But the best result from that would be some fugly looking carts (and would require custom casing), so I think your idea is much more practical.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>kyuusaku</b> [ Sat Oct 13, 2012 3:04 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES/Famicom board - just an idea</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The main issue is that NES and FC have different board thicknesses, so to do it properly one slot would require a separate PCB that is secured to the main one. Not a big deal for expensive development items, but for cheap game production, if customers have only one system the increased cost from two PCBs and additional assembly time probably isn't justified.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
