	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The main issue is that NES and FC have different board thicknesses</div><br /><br />HUH?  all my fami pcbs are ~1.20mm just like my NES boards...<br /><br />I actually planned on doing this for my INL-ROM pcbs.  It's a good idea I think, but there were a few deal breakers for me.  Namely the case issue.  I couldn't answer the question as to what cases they'd go into, so it was hard to define how to ever actually use them.  That and I started to gain other goals for my project which interfered with signal routing and board space so I dropped the idea.<br /><br />If a board were designed for the sole purpose of publishing a game and the case issue were solved I think it'd be a great way to go.  Routing would be pretty simple and assuming it wasn't too complex of mapper setup I'd think you should be able to fit the extra size of a unused 72pin inside a common sized FC/dendy case especially if you used surface mount components.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


